{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17657063","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17657063"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:23:27+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:23:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19094"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"19094","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/19094"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.22,0.15,0,0.15,0.48]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11828"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81545"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11828","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11828"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19094"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66892"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"44"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"527"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"27782"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27872"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27873"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81545","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/81545"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old woman presents with a one day history of abdominal pain that began around her umbilicus and then moved to the right of her abdomen. She describes the initial pain as dull and poorly localised, which then became sharp and well-defined over the ensuing hours. On examination she has a temperature of 37.8\u00b0C and an area of localised tenderness in the right iliac fossa. Ultrasound confirms a distended appendix with surrounding inflammation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the mechanism of the initial periumbilical pain in this condition?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Referred pain from thoracic dermatomes","Release of inflammatory mediators into the peritoneal cavity","Activation of somatic nociceptors in the abdominal wall","Direct irritation of the parietal peritoneum","Stimulation of visceral afferents by appendiceal distension"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe initial periumbilical pain in appendicitis occurs due to \u003Cstrong\u003Estimulation of visceral afferents by appendiceal distension\u003C/strong\u003E. As the appendix becomes obstructed and inflamed, stretch receptors and nociceptors in the wall of the appendix are activated. Because visceral organs are innervated by bilateral, poorly localised nerve fibres, this pain is perceived in the midline around the umbilicus.\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect mechanisms are:\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cul\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EActivation of somatic nociceptors in the abdominal wall\u003C/strong\u003E - This occurs later when inflammation spreads to involve the abdominal wall\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirect irritation of the parietal peritoneum\u003C/strong\u003E - This explains the later, localised right iliac fossa pain when inflammation reaches the peritoneum\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERelease of inflammatory mediators into the peritoneal cavity\u003C/strong\u003E - This is responsible for later peritonitic pain, not the initial periumbilical pain\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReferred pain from thoracic dermatomes\u003C/strong\u003E - Appendicitis pain is not referred from thoracic segments\u003C/li\u003E    \u003C/ul\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EThe migration of pain from periumbilical to right iliac fossa represents progression from visceral to somatic pain as the inflammatory process extends to involve the parietal peritoneum.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Early appendicitis pain is mediated by visceral afferents responding to distension and inflammation of the appendix.","Visceral pain from appendicitis is typically perceived in the periumbilical region due to embryological development of the midgut.","Later appendicitis pain becomes somatic when inflammation involves the parietal peritoneum."],"references":["Laos et al. Challenges in management of acute appendicitis: A narrative review, Current Problems in Surgery, 2024, https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0011384024001576"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66892"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19094"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66892","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/66892"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-26T10:35:51+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-26T10:37:10+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11828"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81545"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"44","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/44"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude79","name":"Pain Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tag